pipeline_messages.content:
You are an expert writing quality judge. You will evaluate three drafts
against a set of personalized rubric criteria. You also have access to the user's
recent conversation history for additional context about their preferences.

The three drafts are:
- Draft A = the **rubric-guided** draft (written following the user's rubric criteria)
- Draft B = the **generic** draft (written with no rubric — just competent writing)
- Draft C = the **original preference** draft (written from the user's stated preferences, before the rubric was created)

DRAFT A (rubric-guided):
Subject: Legacy CSV Export Deprecation — Action Required by [Date 90 Days Out]

We're retiring the legacy CSV export on [specific date]. The replacement is an API-based export that gives your team more control over data structure and delivery frequency — but it requires integration work on your end before that date.

Your current export pipelines will stop functioning when the legacy format is turned off, so your engineering team will need time to build against the new API before the deadline. Full API documentation is available at [link], and your account manager, [Name], is scheduling migration calls for any Meridian team members who need hands-on support.

To book time with [Name] directly, reach them at [email] or [phone].

DRAFT B (generic):
Subject: Important Update: Legacy CSV Export Deprecation in 90 Days

Hi [Name],

We wanted to give you early notice that we'll be retiring the legacy CSV export feature in 90 days. In its place, we're introducing an API-based export that offers significantly more flexibility, better performance, and improved data control — built with customers like Meridian Financial in mind.

We know this requires migration work on your end, and we're fully committed to making that transition smooth. Your dedicated account team will reach out this week to walk through the new API, answer questions, and build a migration plan that fits your timeline.

Thank you for being a valued partner. We're here every step of the way.

DRAFT C (original preference):
Subject: Upcoming Change to CSV Export — Action Required

Hi [Name],

I wanted to give you a heads-up directly: we're deprecating the legacy CSV export feature in 90 days, replacing it with a new API-based export that's significantly more flexible and scalable. This will require some migration work on your end, and I don't want you caught off guard.

We're committed to making this as smooth as possible. Our team is ready to walk you through the new setup, answer technical questions, and work around your timeline.

Can we schedule a call this week or next to get ahead of this together? Just reply here and we'll find a time.

RUBRIC CRITERIA (the user's personalized writing quality criteria):
{
  "rubric": [
    {
      "name": "Reader-Centered Framing",
      "category": "Audience",
      "description": "Write from the reader's position, not about them from the outside. Name what the reader is now dealing with rather than describing or observing their situation. The reader is living it \u2014 the framing should put them at the center, not narrate from a distance.",
      "dimensions": [
        {
          "id": "reader_as_subject",
          "label": "The reader appears as the grammatical subject when discussing impact on them (e.g., 'your plans shifted' not 'this shifts plans')"
        },
        {
          "id": "no_narrator_voice",
          "label": "Impact statements speak directly into the reader's reality rather than observing or commenting on it from outside"
        },
        {
          "id": "specificity_as_empathy",
          "label": "Empathy is conveyed by naming concrete realities the reader faces, not by adding explicit 'I know this is hard' commentary"
        },
        {
          "id": "reader_needs_addressed",
          "label": "Content addresses what the reader needs to know or do, not what the sender needs to justify or explain"
        }
      ],
      "priority": 1
    },
    {
      "name": "Structural Momentum",
      "category": "Structure",
      "description": "The email should orient the reader before delivering news, progress logically through reasoning and impact, and end at the last actionable statement. No lingering after the final next step \u2014 the email ends where the action begins.",
      "dimensions": [
        {
          "id": "grounding_before_news",
          "label": "A brief orienting sentence establishes context before the key information is delivered"
        },
        {
          "id": "reason_follows_news",
          "label": "The 'why' comes early so readers aren't left anxious or guessing"
        },
        {
          "id": "impact_before_process",
          "label": "Reader impact is acknowledged before pivoting to process or logistics, with enough room to breathe"
        },
        {
          "id": "clean_ending_at_action",
          "label": "The email ends on the final actionable statement \u2014 no sign-off filler, thank-yous, or motivational closings after it"
        }
      ],
      "priority": 2
    },
    {
      "name": "Actionable Precision",
      "category": "Content",
      "description": "Next steps include named owners, specific time windows that hold up regardless of when the reader sees the message, and enough concrete detail for people to orient immediately. Vague commitments like 'this week' or 'soon' are replaced with anchored timeframes.",
      "dimensions": [
        {
          "id": "named_owners",
          "label": "Action items are assigned to specific, named individuals"
        },
        {
          "id": "anchored_timeframes",
          "label": "Time references are reader-proof \u2014 they resolve clearly regardless of when the message is opened"
        },
        {
          "id": "concrete_next_steps",
          "label": "The email includes specific, actionable next steps rather than vague intentions"
        },
        {
          "id": "clear_escalation_path",
          "label": "The reader knows exactly where to direct questions or concerns"
        }
      ],
      "priority": 3
    },
    {
      "name": "Functional Sentences",
      "category": "Style",
      "description": "Every sentence must do work. If the previous sentence already carried the weight, don't add a softer follow-up. Cut trailing acknowledgments, performative closings, motivational filler, and anything that sounds right but doesn't actually mean anything.",
      "dimensions": [
        {
          "id": "no_performative_filler",
          "label": "No motivational slogans, rallying cries, or generic encouragements that sound good but carry no information"
        },
        {
          "id": "no_trailing_softeners",
          "label": "Acknowledgment sentences are not followed by a softening or commentary line that dilutes them"
        },
        {
          "id": "each_sentence_earns_place",
          "label": "Every sentence introduces new information, a new action, or a necessary framing shift \u2014 none are redundant"
        },
        {
          "id": "trust_the_sentence",
          "label": "Strong statements are left to land on their own without follow-up lines explaining or cushioning their impact"
        }
      ],
      "priority": 4
    },
    {
      "name": "Professional Directness",
      "category": "Style",
      "description": "Tone is straightforward and confident \u2014 no sugarcoating, no doom and gloom, no defensiveness. Decisions are framed as decisions, not failures. The writer does not manage their own anxiety on the page or preemptively address blame no one is assigning.",
      "dimensions": [
        {
          "id": "decisions_not_failures",
          "label": "Delays or changes are framed as deliberate choices with clear reasoning, not as apologies"
        },
        {
          "id": "no_preemptive_defensiveness",
          "label": "Does not address blame, fault, or finger-pointing that the audience hasn't raised"
        },
        {
          "id": "confident_without_bravado",
          "label": "Tone conveys ownership and clarity without overcorrecting into false optimism or forced confidence"
        },
        {
          "id": "plain_language",
          "label": "Uses direct, plain phrasing rather than corporate hedging or managerial euphemism"
        }
      ],
      "priority": 5
    }
  ],
  "version": 2,
  "source": "criteria_classification",
  "writing_type": "internal team communications / leadership emails",
  "user_goals_summary": "Writes to their team with professional directness, prioritizing the reader's lived reality over the sender's perspective. Values functional brevity \u2014 every sentence must earn its place \u2014 and trusts specificity to carry empathy rather than adding commentary about it. Emails should end cleanly at the point of action.",
  "coaching_notes": "This user has a sharp instinct for the difference between writing that describes a situation and writing that speaks into it \u2014 they will consistently reject narrator-voice framing. They cut toward less text in every round; when in doubt, trust the strongest sentence to land on its own and delete the follow-up. They treat performative empathy and motivational filler as equivalent failures \u2014 both signal that the writer is managing their own comfort rather than serving the reader."
}

